The barrel and action metal is in excellent condition with smooth, deep, dark bluing. Stock is in good condition with a few handling/storage marks and flaking varnish, as it typical of arsenal refurbed Mosins, and a non-structural crack at the left of the aft section of the receiver. title: For Sale:  SPT: Mosin Unissued Tikka M39 AZF marked on Sako stock
postcontent: *Sold Pending Trade*If you know Mosins, then you know that of the 37+million made, they only made 5000 M39s with Tikka barrels. Of the 5000 Tikka barreled M39s only some made their way to North America, and fewer still remain unfired since refurb. Not the absolute rarest mosin ever, but most collectors I know have never seen one of these in person. Here is your chance to own one.1942 Tikka AZF marked M39 with Sako stock and fresh rearsenal:This 42 Tikka M39 appears to be fresh and unfired since refurb. The hex receiver has what appears to be the faint remnant of an imperial crest and two AZF "Artillerie Zeugs Fabrik" Austrian arsenal marks of different sizes. This implies that the receiver may have cycled through Austrian ownership more than once?I am unable to make out the markings on the bottom of the tang to ID the maker. Looks like a number 9... or maybe a 6, not sure what else, maybe a "1" or an arrow? See the picture and judge for yourself.The blueing is very strong and looks new throughout the rifle. In the barrel the rifling is bright and crisp with no wear at all evident. Since I received this rifle direct from the importer and it still had the remnants of the arsenal hang tag on it, I think it is relatively safe to assume this rifle had not been fired since being refurbished with the new Tikka barrel. The non-counterbored Tikka barrel is Finn matched to the bolt handle and stamped on the left side with "7.62x53R" (yes, that is a 3) , "3600" and "SA". According to 7.62x54r.net, the 1940's Tikka barreled M39s are an 8 of 10 on the rarity scale, so not your everyday Sako or VKT. :) I found the following at MosinNagant.net, which describes the Tikka flavored M39s :"Total production of the m/39 rifle during the wartime period of 1940-1945 was a total of 96,800 rifles. Total production total of the m/39 including post war modifications is approximately 102,000.A relatively new barrel marking for the m/39 rifle was recently introduced with the last import of these rifles. It consists of barrels made by Tikkakoski. These barrels carry the standard Tikkakoski marking of a "T" inside an inverted triangle enclosed in a circle. These barrels are originally m/91 barrels that have been modified to m/39 specifications. The barrels are shortened and recrowned and were used to replace badly worn or damaged barrels of m/39’s when they were re-inspected or passing through a depot level repair/refurbishment cycle. It is not known what depot performed the repairs but the total number of barrels used for this procedure is known-5,000. This makes the Tikka barreled m/39 quite a rare find. Those known and observed have all been in extraordinary shape indicating little use after the refurbishment. Many still exhibit the arsenal tag affixed to the barrel band."The arsenal tag itself is missing, but the wire hanger and brass grommet with a small bit of the tag paper is still attached to the front barrel band side sling attachment point. I have shaken the box no less than 5 separate times hoping that somehow, magically, the arsenal tag will fall out, having just come loose in the shipping box. No luck.The main bolt serial number has been scrubbed. The magazine floor plate and butt plate have different serial numbers. The toe spliced Sako wartime stock has been sanded so the Sako cartouche is a bit faint, with the stock maker's cartouche just barely too light to definitively tell what who the stock maker was. The end of the stock and handguard have been trimmed back from the barrel so they don't touch the barrel (barrel is free floated!). The recoil lug bottom shim and tang shim are in place. Also interesting is that the receiver has been very nicely bedded. Of the 3 x M39 Mosins I have this is the only one that is bedded. You can see the stamps on the bottom of the receiver left impressions in the bedding compound.The cleaning rod has crosshatch knurling. The rear sight spring is plum colored. The front sight appears to be marked 7.6. The barrel is not counterbored.I don't need to sell this, so don't bother with low-ball offers.Might consider a trade, but it would have to be something special to get my attention. I am considering an offer to trade this Tikka M39 for either an M1 Carbine or M1 Garand.Prefer face to face sale on the West side of Burlington, NC, but willing to ship to your FFL or C&R at your expense.

title: For Sale:  Custom, Attorney Drafted NFA Gun Trust
postcontent: I am a Florida licensed attorney and offer comprehensive NFA gun trust drafting services. My trusts are 20+ pages and cover the numerous issues related to NFA items for you and your beneficiaries. A gun trust enables you to purchase suppressors, short barreled rifles and fully automatic rifles without the hassles (and often impossibility) of a chief law enforcement officer signature as well as other bureaucratic red tape. As a firearms enthusiast, I want to see more people enjoying the benefits of NFA items and, because this isn't my primary source of income, I can offer my services at $199 for a trust. This includes an initial in-person or phone consultation to determine how to best serve your needs, all fees and documents, an electronic copy of your final trust documents, a guide to how to best use your trust as well as an appendix of ATF advisory letters and forms. While there are cheaper “fill-in-the-blank” trusts available online, the ATF has given negative feedback on many of these as not being well drafted and having the potential to expose the user to criminal and civil penalties. Not only am I licensed and in good standing in Florida, but I am also licensed and in good standing in Arkansas and Texas and can assist with trusts in those states as well. I prefer cash, but am willing to accept trades of equivalent value at my discretion. Please contact me, David Kronenfeld, at 2ndamendmenttrusts@gmail.com to inquire about my services.
